ULCERATIVE COLITIS: THE HIGH-PERFORMANCE PLAYBOOK
Evidence-Based Remission & Reversal Protocol (2024–2026)

SECTION 1: CURRENT GOLD STANDARD (2024–2026)
The Biologic & Small Molecule Hierarchy
TNF Inhibitors — Still first-line biologics for moderate-to-severe UC

Infliximab (Remicade), Adalimumab (Humira), Golimumab (Simponi)
Clinical remission rates: 20–40% at 1 year (real-world, not trial-inflated)
Limitation: Primary non-response in ~30–40% of patients; secondary loss of response common

IL-12/23 Inhibitors — The current gastroenterologist favorite for durability

Ustekinumab (Stelara) — FDA-approved for UC since 2019, now heavily used
Remission at 44 weeks: ~24% clinical remission (UNIFI trial), but real-world practitioners report higher
Lower immunosuppression burden than TNFs — preferred for patients with infection risk

IL-23 Inhibitors (p19) — The 2024–2025 frontrunner class

Mirikizumab (Omvoh) — FDA-approved May 2023. 12-week induction clinical remission: 24.2% vs 13.3% placebo. 40-week maintenance: 49.9% remission (LUCENT trials)
Risankizumab (Skyrizi) — approved for UC 2024. 12-week induction: 20% clinical remission; maintenance at 52 weeks: ~40%+
Why gastroenterologists are moving here: Selective p19 blockade spares IL-12, preserving Th1 immunity — better infection profile than TNFs, comparable or superior efficacy

JAK Inhibitors — Fast-acting, oral, highly effective

Tofacitinib (Xeljanz) — first-in-class; still used but carries cardiovascular/thrombosis warnings (black box)
Upadacitinib (Rinvoq) — JAK1-selective, cleaner safety profile. U-ACHIEVE trial: 26% remission at 8 weeks (induction), 42% at 52 weeks. Currently the fastest-acting agent available — significant symptom control within 2 weeks
Filgotinib (Jyseleca) — available in EU; JAK1-selective; similar profile to upadacitinib
When used: Moderate-severe UC failing one or more biologics; patients needing rapid response
Real risk: JAK inhibitors carry FDA black box for MAALOX (malignancy, major adverse cardiovascular events) — risk stratification required

Ozanimod (Zeposia) — S1P receptor modulator, oral

Approved 2021; acts by sequestering lymphocytes in lymph nodes
10-week remission: ~18%; 52-week: ~37%
Advantage: No biologic immunosuppression mechanism — different risk profile
Growing use in patients who fail biologics or have serious infection history

Etrasimod (Velsipity) — Newer S1P modulator, approved 2023

ELEVATE UC trials: 27% remission at 12 weeks vs 7% placebo — significantly outperformed ozanimod in trials
Once-daily oral; fast cardiac offset (no first-dose monitoring required like older S1P agents)
Increasingly preferred over ozanimod by prescribers


What Top GI Specialists Are Actually Doing Now (2025)

Treat-to-target strategy is the dominant paradigm: target mucosal healing, not just symptom control. Endoscopic remission is the new benchmark.
Combination therapy (biologic + immunomodulator like azathioprine or methotrexate) used selectively to reduce immunogenicity against biologics
Therapeutic drug monitoring (TDM) — measuring drug trough levels and antibodies proactively, not just when failing. This alone extends biologic durability significantly
Positioning shift: Many specialists now reaching for upadacitinib or IL-23 inhibitors earlier (step-up compressed), rather than cycling through multiple TNFs
De-escalation trials: Patients in deep remission (endoscopic + histologic) being offered spacing/stepping down — this is growing


SECTION 2: CUTTING-EDGE & EXPERIMENTAL
Fecal Microbiota Transplant (FMT)
Status: PROMISING — Not yet FDA-approved for UC, but data is compelling

Multiple RCTs now completed. Meta-analyses show: UC clinical remission with FMT ~28% vs 9% placebo (Paramsothy et al., Lancet 2017; confirmed in subsequent trials)
TOPF trial (2024): Multi-donor, intensive FMT protocol — 32% endoscopic remission at 8 weeks vs 9% placebo
Key variables that predict success:

Donor selection is everything — "super donors" with specific microbiome profiles drive outcomes; random donor FMT is mediocre
Frequency matters: weekly FMT over 8 weeks outperforms single-dose
Route matters: colonoscopic delivery > enema > capsule for UC specifically


What's holding it back: No FDA approval for UC; requires IND (Investigational New Drug) pathway for clinical use in the US
Current access: Clinical trials (ClinicalTrials.gov), academic medical centers, or travel to Australia/Canada where protocols are more accessible
Bottom line: Among the most mechanistically sound experimental approaches; if you can access a high-quality protocol with vetted donor selection, the risk/benefit is favorable


Microbiome-Targeted Therapies

SER-287 (spores-based microbiome therapy) — Phase 2 failed to meet endpoints; development paused
VE303 — defined bacterial consortium; Phase 2 data expected 2025; targets C. difficile niche but microbiome normalization may have UC implications
Lactobacillus/Bifidobacterium cocktails: Clinical data weak for inducing remission; at best adjunctive for maintenance


Stem Cell Therapies
Status: EXPERIMENTAL — Early human data, not yet clinical standard

Mesenchymal Stem Cells (MSCs): Immunomodulatory, anti-inflammatory, mucosal-healing mechanism

Phase 1/2 trials show safety; some remission signals in refractory UC
Cx601 (darvadstrocel) — approved in EU for Crohn's fistulas; UC application in trials


Hematopoietic Stem Cell Transplant (HSCT): Used in severe refractory IBD cases; significant risk/benefit calculation; not mainstream


Peptides & Regenerative Approaches
BPC-157 (Body Protection Compound)

Status: PROMISING but unregulated — no completed human RCTs for UC specifically
Mechanism: Promotes angiogenesis, upregulates growth hormone receptor signaling, reduces gut inflammation in animal models
Rat/rodent IBD models show impressive mucosal healing
Real-world use: Significant underground use in IBD community via compounding pharmacies; anecdotal remission reports, no controlled human data
Risk: Unregulated, no long-term human safety data; potential tumor promotion signal in some cancer models

Larazotide Acetate (AT-1001)

Tight junction stabilizer — targets intestinal permeability
Phase 2 celiac data positive; UC application being explored
Mechanistically sound for the "leaky gut → immune activation" pathway

Phosphatidylcholine (LPC)

UC patients show significantly depleted mucus phosphatidylcholine vs healthy controls
Retarded-release phosphatidylcholine (RRPC) trials show remission induction comparable to mesalamine in left-sided UC
Underused in the US; available in Germany as Colafalk


IL-1β & Inflammasome Targeting

Canakinumab (IL-1β antibody) — trials ongoing for UC; strong mechanistic rationale in neutrophil-driven disease
NLRP3 inhibitors — Inzomelid and others; early-phase; targets a key inflammatory amplification node


SECTION 3: PATIENT-LED BREAKTHROUGHS
Diet Strategies — Ranked by Evidence
1. Specific Carbohydrate Diet (SCD)
Proven for symptom reduction; limited remission data

Eliminates complex carbohydrates (grains, lactose, sucrose) that feed dysbiotic bacteria
PRODUCE trial (JAMA, 2022): SCD vs Mediterranean diet — both showed clinical improvement; SCD slightly superior for corticosteroid-free remission at 12 weeks (~47% vs 43%)
Best for: Mild-moderate UC with significant dietary trigger patterns
Protocol: Strict phase (meats, eggs, certain vegetables/fruits, aged cheeses) → gradual reintroduction

2. Low-FODMAP Diet
Proven for symptom management; does NOT induce mucosal remission

Dramatically reduces gas, bloating, urgency — quality of life improvement is significant
Reduces fermentable substrates that drive gut dysbiosis and gas production
Critical caveat: Long-term FODMAP restriction starves beneficial bacteria (Bifidobacterium) — use short-term (4–6 weeks), then targeted reintroduction
Best as: Acute flare symptom management tool, not a permanent protocol

3. Mediterranean Diet
Proven for remission maintenance and prevention

PRODUCE trial data (above); anti-inflammatory omega-3 profile; prebiotic fiber supports Faecalibacterium prausnitzii (the most depleted commensal in active UC)
Most sustainable long-term option with the strongest systemic anti-inflammatory benefit
High-oleic olive oil specifically: activates PPAR-γ in colonocytes — directly anti-inflammatory in colonic epithelium

4. Carnivore / Animal-Based Diet
Promising — strong anecdotal signal, weak trial evidence

Mechanistic rationale: eliminates all plant antigens, fermentable fibers that may perpetuate inflammation in sensitized guts
Real-world: Numerous documented cases of full symptom resolution and endoscopic remission in patient communities (Carnivore MD data, Dr. Shawn Baker case series)
The problem: No RCTs. Eliminates prebiotic fiber needed for microbiome diversity — potential long-term microbiome consequences unknown
Best use case: Short-term elimination phase (8–12 weeks) to achieve symptom control, then systematic reintroduction
Who it works for: Patients failing all other diets; those with significant food-trigger patterns; aggressive phenotypes unresponsive to conventional elimination

5. Elemental / Semi-Elemental Diets
Proven for mucosal rest and remission induction in refractory cases

Pre-digested nutrition; minimal antigenic load on the gut
2–4 week elemental formula protocol can induce remission and reduce inflammatory markers
Not sustainable long-term; used as a reset protocol


